Problem 1: Dendrograms (50pts)

In this lab, we will again work with the student performance dataset used in Homework6. Heres the code to read in the data:

Details about the dataset are found here.

Its actually easier to make fine-looking dendrograms in base R, so we are going to focus on using base R (instead of ggplot) for making dendrograms.

  1. (10pts) First, perform the following steps:
  • Create a subset of the student data that only contains the four quantitative variables RaisedHands, VisitedResources, AnnouncementsView, and Discussion. Define this as data.subset.
data.subset = subset(data, select = c(RaisedHands, VisitedResources, AnnouncementsView, Discussion))
  • Standardize your variables by dividing each column by its standard deviation.
data.subset = apply(data.subset, MARGIN = 2, FUN = function(x) x/sd(x))
  • Create a distance matrix using the Euclidean distance using the dist function. Define this as data.subset.dist.
data.subset.dist = dist(data.subset)

If youve done this correctly, you should be able to run the following line of code:

dim(as.matrix(data.subset.dist))
## [1] 480 480

You should get a 480-by-480 matrix, which represents the distance matrix for this dataset. (If you dont, something must have gone wrong - please ask for help if you get stuck.) Furthermore, you should be able to run the following lines of code:

mean(as.matrix(data.subset.dist)[1,])
## [1] 2.668366
mean(as.matrix(data.subset.dist)[,1])
## [1] 2.668366

After youve done this: In 1-3 sentences, explain why the two numbers produced by the above code are the same. (Feel free to wait until after the lab to write a formal answer to this part, but please ask for help if you dont immediately know the answer to this one.)

Any distance matrix is an \(n \times n\) matrix, where \(n\) denotes the number of subjects. Any \([i,j]\) entry of the matrix denotes the distance between subject \(i\) and subject \(j\). Thus, the first row of the matrix denotes the distances between the first subject and all the other subjects; similarly, the first column also denotes the distances between the first subject and all the other subjects. In other words, the \(i\)th row and \(i\)th column of any distance matrix will contain the same numbers. Thus, both numbers above represent the average distance between the first subject and all other subjects.

  1. (15pts) It can be helpful to color the tree by the clusters it naturally divides itself into. To do this, youll need the R package dendextend, so please install that package if you havent already. Be sure to load the library with the line library(dendextend).

Within the dendextend library, there is a function called set that is commonly used to alter aspects of a dendrogram plot. Unfortunately, you can only set one aspect of a dendrogram at a time, so it is a bit tedious to use (i.e., you have to write multiple lines of code using the set function). However, its not that hard once you learn how to do it. Youll have to use the set function on the homework.

The following lines of code produces a dendrogram with branches colored by the \(k = 3\) clusters identified by the dendrogram:

library(dendextend)
#what are the k = 3 clusters identified by the dendrogram?
student.hc.dend = set(student.hc.dend, "branches_k_color", k = 3)
plot(student.hc.dend)

Note that student.hc.dend must be correctly defined; you should have done this in Part B.

In your submission, please turn in the dendrogram with \(k = 3\) colors. However, on your own, try setting \(k = 2\), \(k = 4\), and \(k = 5\). Then, answer the following in 1-3 sentences: How is this code deciding which branches to color (e.g., which ones should be one color, which ones should be another color, etc.)? Your answer doesnt have to be mathematical; your grandma should be able to understand your answer. (Or if your grandma is a statisticianyour grandpa.) You can wait until after the lab to write a formal answer, but ask for help if you dont immediately know the answer here!

Setting "branches_k_color" splits the dendrogram into \(k\) different colors, and these splits occur where the tree splits first, going from top to bottom. For example, lets start at the top of our \(k = 3\) tree: The tree splits into two pieces (denoted by a horizontal line around 6), so these two branches will receive two different colors for sure. Then, the next highest horizontal line is around 5 - this is the next time that the tree splits, so the color is split as well. At this point we have all \(k = 3\) of our colors, so the whole dendrogram is colored according to these splits.

  1. (15pts) Part C shows us the \(k = 3\) clusters that the dendrogram is identifying. To see if the clusters align with a categorical variable in the data, we can color the leaf labels at the bottom of the plot by a categorical variable.

Well color the leaves by the Grade variable, because it also has \(k = 3\) levels. Because were using base R, we first need to define a vector of colors based on the Grade variable. The following line of code does this for you:

grade.colors = ifelse(data$Grade == "H", "blue",
                      ifelse(data$Grade == "M", "green", "red"))

where data is the dataset I defined at the beginning of this lab. (There are also fancier ways to do this in tidyverse, but Im being old-school here.)

Now were going to use the set function again to define the color of the leaf labels at the bottom of your dendrogram. To do this, run the following line of code only after youve successfully run the code from Part C:

student.hc.dend = set(student.hc.dend, "labels_colors", order_value = TRUE, grade.colors)
plot(student.hc.dend)

I asked you to run the above code only after youve run the code from Part C, because that way, the branch colors and leaf colors will have been set. Having order_value = TRUE is also very important - you should always use it when setting the leaf label colors in this way. In the background, the dendrogram is reordering the data, so order_value = TRUE is telling R, Hey, my colors are in the order of my data, not the order you created, R!

Your submission for this problem should have a dendrogram with branches that are three different colors and leaf labels that are three different colors defined by the Grade variable. Then, answer the following in 1-3 sentences: To what extent are the three clusters identified by the dendrogram (i.e., the branch colors) just the three Grade values (i.e., the leaf colors) in the dataset? For example, does each cluster identified by the dendrogram consist of just one type of Grade, or at least mostly one type of Grade? Or is there a mix of Grade types across all of the clusters?

Again, you can wait until after the lab to fully answer this question, but be sure to ask for help if youre not immediately sure what the answer will be. Also, note that I decided to make the leaf colors red, green, and blue, which will correspond to the branch colors; but in general, the leaf colors do not have to correspond to the branch colors.

For each of the three clusters identified by the dendrogram (denoted by the branch colors), there is at least some heterogeneity in terms of the Grade variable, but some Grade values are definitely more prominent than others for each of the clusters. In particular:

  • The right-hand cluster tends to have students with high grades (denoted by blue leaf labels). There are also a few students with medium grades (denoted by green leaf labels).
  • The center cluster tends to have students with medium grades. There are also some students with high grades.
  • The left-hand cluster is the most heterogeneous, but it tends to have students with low grades (denoted by red leaf labels). There are also a fair number of students with medium grades.

Problem 2: Principal Component Analysis (50 points)

Now we will visualize the student dataset using principal component analysis (PCA). In particular, we will reduce the 4-dimensional dataset to just 2 dimensions. This isnt a large dimension reduction, but it will help us understand what PCA is doing.

  1. (5pts): First, perform the following steps (the first two you should have already done in Part A of Problem 1, so you can just copy-and-paste your code here):

data.subset = subset(data, select = c(RaisedHands, VisitedResources, AnnouncementsView, Discussion))
  • Center your variables by subtracting from each column its mean (i.e., redefine the column as the column minus its mean). If youre unsure how to do this step, ask for help or see the Lecture 17 R demo.
data.subset = apply(data.subset, MARGIN = 2, FUN = function(x) x - mean(x))
  • Standardize your variables by dividing each column by its standard deviation.
data.subset = apply(data.subset, MARGIN = 2, FUN = function(x) x/sd(x))

After youve performed these steps, the following lines of code will give you 1 and approximately 0, respectively:

## [1] 1
mean(data.subset[,1])
## [1] 4.079762e-17

Its okay that the mean is not exactly zero; this is just due to rounding error in R.

  1. (15pts) Now we will make an elbow plot, where the proportion of total variation of each component is on the y-axis, and the component number is on the x-axis. To make an elbow plot, follow these steps:
  • After data.pca is defined, run the following line of code:
summary(data.pca)$importance["Proportion of Variance",]
##     PC1     PC2     PC3     PC4 
## 0.62715 0.20387 0.09448 0.07450

You should get back a 4-length vector, where each element corresponds to the proportion of variation (which you used in Part B). Define this 4-length vector as varProps.

varProps = summary(data.pca)$importance["Proportion of Variance",]
  • Now, make a scatterplot where varProps is on the y-axis and the numbers 1, 2, 3, 4 (1:4) are on the x-axis. You can do this using the base R plot() function (as shown in the Lecture 17 R demo) or you can use ggplot() by putting varProps and 1:4 into its own data.frame (and then using geom_point() and geom_line()). The goal is to craete the classic elbow plot that we discussed at the end of last lecture.
varProps.df = data.frame(component = 1:4, varProps)
library(tidyverse)
ggplot(varProps.df, aes(x = component, y = varProps)) + geom_point() + geom_line()

After youve made the elbow plot: Where do you think the elbow is in this plot? In other words, how many components do you think should be used when visualizing this dataset? Provide a 1-2 sentence explanation of your answer.

From this plot, it appears that the elbow is at \(k = 2\), suggesting that \(k = 2\) components should be used when visualizing this dataset. We say that the elbow occurs at \(k = 2\) because the proportion of variation appears to decrease a lot from 1 to 2, but appears to level off afterwards (i.e., the line appears to become much more flat after \(k = 2\)). This suggests that the marginal benefit of including more than \(k = 2\) components is fairly small, thereby suggesting that it is appropriate to only use \(k = 2\) components. [Note, however, that a similar argument could be made for \(k = 3\) - that is an equally good response to this question. However, \(k = 1\) and \(k = 4\) are definitely incorrect.]

Note: Because this is already a low-dimensional dataset, the choice of elbow may not be as clear - just provide your reasoning, regardless of your choice. Please ask for help if its unclear how you identify the elbow in an elbow plot in general.

  1. (15pts) Now we will make a scatterplot of the first two principal components using ggplot(), colored by Grade within the original data (defined at the beginning of this lab). To do this, follow these steps:

#the principal components, which are

prinComps = X%*%data.pca$rotation
#convert to a data.frame

This assumes that youve already defined data.subset and data.pca correctly (see Question 2A and Question 2B, respectively). It is your responsibility to understand what this code is doing - ask for help if you dont understand!

  • Note that data$Grade provides the grade of each student in the dataset (either low, medium, or high). Add Grade to the prinComps dataset.
prinComps$Grade = data$Grade
  • Now you should have a single data.frame called prinComps, which contains the principal components and Grade. Using this, make the desired scatterplot, which the first principal component (PC1) on the x-axis and the second principal component (PC2) on the y-axis, with points colored by Grade.

[For this part, all you have to do is make the desired scatterplot. However, you should ask yourself: Does Grade seem to be associated with any of the principal components?]

ggplot(prinComps, aes(x = PC1, y = PC2)) + geom_point(aes(color = Grade))

Yes, it appears that Grade is associated with the first principal component: Students with a low first prinicpal component tend to have a low grade, and students with a high first principal component tend to have a high grade. However, there does not seem to be a strong association between Grade and the second principal component.

[Note: If you go back to the Lecture 15 R Demo, youll find that this plot is actually identical to the equivalent MDS plot for these data. This is because, when the Euclidean distance is used, the first two dimensions of MDS are actually equivalent to the first two principal components. (Discussing as to why is outside the scope of this class - but in short, it is because both MDS and PCA rely on an eigenvector decomposition of the covariates covariance matrix.) PCA provides some additional value over MDS, however: The elbow plot allows us to determine what \(k\) should be, and it is more straightforward to determine how the principal components are related to the original variables in the data, as well see on the homework.]

  1. (10pts) In Part D you should have made a scatterplot of the first two principal components. In this part, copy-and-paste your Part D code, and add a single linear regression line to the plot (without confidence intervals). Be sure there is a single regression line in the plot.
ggplot(prinComps, aes(x = PC1, y = PC2)) + geom_point(aes(color = Grade)) + geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

After youve made the plot, answer the following question in 1-2 sentences: Why is it totally unsurprising that the linear regression line is completely flat?

As discussed in class, the principal components are defined such that each principal component is uncorrelated with the rest of the principal components. Thus, the first and second principal components are by definition uncorrelated with each other, resulting in a flat regression line.
